<Base title="Hay. The Phantasmagorical Work of Anna Raczyńska — Michalina Sablik">
  <div class="container page-content">
    <h1>Hay. The Phantasmagorical Work of Anna Raczyńska</h1>
    <p class="exhibition-detail-venue">Curatorial essay | Published in "Old Habits, New Beginnings"</p>
    <div class="exhibition-detail-body">
      <p>The essay explores the paradoxes of border crossing and fluid identity, opening with an autobiographical account of returning to Bielsko-Biała, a Polish industrial town.</p>
      <p>It discusses how crossing EU borders creates questions about belonging: An exotic homo sovieticus? Poor but sexy? A Euro-orphan? These labels, imposed and internalized, reveal the shifting terrain of identity within a post-socialist, increasingly integrated Europe.</p>
      <p>The text examines how identities are fluid constructs shaped by personal history, memory, and invisible systems of power, drawing on Stuart Hall's writings on cultural identity and Slavoj Žižek's theorization of phantasms.</p>
      <p>Key artworks analyzed include "Future Primitive" (2021) — a harvest wreath composed of Polish wheat arranged in a euro symbol shape, collapsing folk tradition into economic iconography — and "A Monument to What Weighs Nothing but Costs Everything" (2021) — an oversized ATM card symbolizing how individual identity becomes reduced to economic dimensions, how personhood is flattened into data points and credit scores.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</Base>
